default&#xa0;
defaultQ176default 
defaultJohn Robertson:default And what are you going to do about it?
default              
defaultGregory Barker:default David, what are we doing? Do you want to talk about our strategy?
defaultDavid defaultWagstaffdefault:default I could talk at length about our strategy, but I will try to speak specifically to that question.
defaultWe certainly think that that is a good potential solution. There is obviously a difference between saying that it is a good idea and making it happen—the Minister has already explained that we are not likely to be forcing people into particular solutions. The potential for heat networks and exploiting currently under-utilised forms of heat is one of the things that we said quite a lot about in 
defaultThe Future of H
defaulte
defaultating: Meeting the C
defaulthallenge
default, which we published in March.
default              
defaultNew-build homes are being put on to heat networks at the moment—quite often driven by planning, for example in Greater London—and we have set up an entirely new uni
defaultt in the Department called the Heat Network Delivery U
defaultnit, which is specifically working with local authorities with both financial support and expertise from within the team to expand existing heat networks, to plan for new heat networks and to look at all the different forms of heat that you can exploit. The fundamental thing about a heat network is that, once you have the pipes there, you can look for lots of different heat, including low-grade heat and heat pumps. It is easier to envisage a set of options for low-carbon heating that goes on to a network than it is to try to transform every one of 25 million individual domestic properties.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ177default 
defaultJohn Robertson:default So would it be fair to say that you are at an early stage in this process.
defaultDavid defaultWagstaffdefault:default It is certainly fair to say that we do not have as many heat networks in this country as there are in some other European countries.
default              
defaultGregory Barker:default I think David is being a little bit modest.
defaultJohn Robertson:default We are not used to that.
defaultGregory Barker:default defaultActually, the fact that for the first time we now have a heat network unit in DECC recognises that this is a big opportunity. For the first time we have a strategy to deliver heat networks. We launched a round of funding in the autumn, and 100 local authorities responded positively.  Of those 100, 31 submitted full applications for 54 different heat network projects. We are not supplying the actual capital to roll out the projects, but we are providing small amounts of resource to pull together a heat network plan locally, which will give them the support to draw up a plan that they can deliver on. It is early days, but there is now a plan, and we actually have capacity in DECC to work with local authorities to roll this out.
