default&#xa0;
defaultQ267default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default They are paying a great deal more for their electricity in this country under the current deals than they expect to pay. From memory, they said that it is two-and-a-quarter times more expensive to buy electricity here than in 
defaultFrance
default.
default              
defaultGregory Barker:default We take carbon leakage extremely seriously.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ268default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default This is a straight price mechanism issue. Why will industry be based here if they can go to 
defaultFrance
default and the 
defaultUnited States
default and buy energy much more cheaply?
defaultGregory Barker:default It is a very legitimate question, but there isn’t a single answer. We take carbon leakage extremely seriously. One of the first things I did after coming to this job was to dig behind the figures by going to Germany and trying to work out why a country that was able to deploy and pay for the deployment of the largest level of 
defaultrenewables
default in Europe was simultaneously able to dramatically increase its share of the world market for manufactured goods. 
defaultGermany continues to have a very robust manufacturing sector, while deploying 
defaultrenewables
default and paying for that deployment in a way that, to date, significantly outstrips the 
defaultUK
default. The reason for that is not because energy prices are generally cheaper for industry and commerce—they are not—but because 
defaultGermany
default allows very significant exceptions for energy-intensive industries, which are, by and large, the minority of the manufacturing industry. Where there is a very high energy load as an essential part of an industry’s production process, in 
defaultGermany
default they get a very substantial rebate on their energy bills. 
defaultFor the German economy, this amounts to about €5 billion per year handed back to that small section of energy-intensive industries as compensation for policy costs. We recognise that, and it is why last year the Chancellor announced an initial sum of £250 million for a compensation scheme. We recognise that that does not go the full distance in terms of compensation, but it is a step in the right direction. Unfortunately, we have to take into account the record deficit and the state of public finances inherited by the coalition.
defaultWe are clear that more needs to be done to assist energy-intensive industries. Clearly, there are two drivers. One is the cost of Government policy on energy-intensive industries, and what we need to do to mitigate that. The other is the underlying cost of energy. These are two quite different factors. Consider 
defaultFrance
default and 
defaultAmerica
default. Obviously, 
defaultAmerica
default is benefiting from the fact that it is a closed market for gas—or at least has been to date—and it has enjoyed extraordinarily low gas prices. That has a very beneficial effect on its economy. At the same time, it has also been able to reduce its carbon emissions, by switching quite significantly from coal to gas.
defaultWe are very keen to encourage the same gas revolution here that there has been in 
defaultAmerica
default, by the application of 
defaultfracking
default. Tomorrow, we will announce a further iteration in our 
defaultfracking
default strategy. However, at this early stage, we are cautious about suggesting 
defaultthat we can fully replicate here the price collapse that we saw in 
defaultAmerica
default, not least because of the different shape of the market and also the geological potential. There is the issue of the appetite of 
defaultEurope
default as a whole to embrace 
defaultfracking
default, given that we have a Europe-wide market for gas. At the moment, the 
defaultUK
default and probably 
defaultPoland
default are grasping this opportunity, but there is some resistance elsewhere in the EU.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ269default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default I now come to the questions I was going to ask. The UK Energy Research Centre is calling for a gas network strategy group to examine the future role of gas networks in the 
defaultUK
default. Are you going to establish such a group?
defaultGregory Barker:default That doesn’t form part of my primary brief, but my officials might know. Mr 
defaultFallon
default leads on gas.
defaultDavid defaultWagstaffdefault:default I’m afraid I don’t know. It is a perfectly reasonable thought, and I don’t think there is a particularly strong view. I am afraid that I haven’t actually asked the person who would be responsible for that, so I don’t know what the answer is.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ270default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default Well, going back to some of the questions Albert asked before, you gave two answers to his question about gas connections and gas disconnections being time-based,
default 
defaultas it were. I understand that. How are you going to deal with the transformation process from an expanding gas network to one that is much smaller?
defaultDavid defaultWagstaffdefault:default I think that is probably one of the hardest questions which could be asked. The big transformational changes that have happened to the energy system in the 
defaultUK
default by and large took place in a pre-privatisation world. We can look to what happened in the early ’70s,
default 
defaultfor example, when we went from town gas to natural gas, but that happened under regional boards rather than private companies. I think all countries will have to go through a similar transitional challenge, so this is not something the 
defaultUK
default will have to answer on its own. It is also worth pointing out that, despite the difficulties which are faced by people with off-gas-grid homes, the 
defaultUK
default has probably got a more extensive gas grid than virtually any other developed country.
default              
defaultGregory Barker:default Which would be of benefit if we are able to develop 
defaultfracking
default here.
defaultDavid defaultWagstaffdefault:default And we are not saying that the retreat from a gas grid is inevitable. That is an important point about the whole-system modelling that we have been doing.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ271default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default Before you finish, can you expand on that point? The implication of what you were saying before was about gas shrinking, as you move to a much greater percentage of electricity.
defaultDavid defaultWagstaffdefault:default Undoubtedly, an implication in hitting an 80% reduction in carbon emissions in 2050 is that we will be burning significantly less fossil fuels, including gas. It is without doubt the case that not as much gas will be used, assuming, of course, that that is still natural gas. One possible scenario would be for something else to go through the gas pipes that is not natural gas, and I mentioned hydrogen earlier in passing.
defaultIt is also worth noting that a lot of customers on the gas grid are industrial and commercial customers, so even while domestic users may not be burning gas, we haven’t ever said that there would be no gas available for industry. So it is likely that parts of the network will still be in operation. The question then becomes: which parts of the network won’t be in operation and how do you effect that change? That is a very long-term question, and we have not been definitive in our answer to that because we simply do not know. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ272default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default How will you explain to the electorate, Minister, that they can no longer have gas?
defaultGregory Barker:default I think you’re pushing quite far into the future. I appreciate your confidence that we will still be in government in the 2030s. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ273default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default I am fascinated by how a Conservative Government, who supposedly believe in choice, will come out with the Stalinist view that you will no longer be able to have gas piped to your house.
defaultGregory Barker:default But I think we are talking about something that is decades ahead. That certainly will not be in our next manifesto.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ274default 
defaultGraham Stringer:default So you don’t look forward to explaining that?
defaultGregory Barker:default I look forward to being politically alive to explain it. As David said, we are talking about something that really will not be a policy choice until the 2030s or possibly later.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ275default 
defaultJohn Robertson:default The point is that no preparatory work has been done.
default              
